   =20
      ICBC
   =20
 =20

In the olden days, the way stock and bond trading worked is that you and I =
would agree on a trade (over the phone, on the floor of the stock exchange,=
 etc.), and we=E2=80=99d each make a little note of it on a scrap of paper,=
 and at the end of the day our clerks would collect the scraps of paper and=
 figure out what we=E2=80=99d bought and sold, and then the clerks would go=
 down to the vault in the basement, and my clerk would get out the bond cer=
tificates I sold to you, and your clerk would get out a wad of cash, and ou=
r clerks would walk across the streets of Manhattan, and my clerk would han=
d your clerk the bonds and your clerk would hand my clerk the cash, and the=
n our trade would be settled. And this process took days, and had some fail=
ure rate, because we and our clerks were only human and the vaults were big=
 and poorly organized and our handwriting, on the scraps of paper, was not =
always legible.
In 2023, almost all of this has been rendered abstract and put on computers=
. The bonds are entries on a computer, the cash is an entry on a computer, =
the scraps=C2=A0of paper are computers, the floor of the stock exchange is =
mostly a computer, the whole process, from start to finish, occurs on compu=
ters and often doesn=E2=80=99t involve any human actions at all. (It still =
often takes days?)=C2=A0This, of course, concentrates a lot of risk in the =
computers: If the computer systems fail, then all the trades fail, global f=
inance is plunged into chaos, etc. So people put a lot of thought and effor=
t and money into making the computer systems very robust and secure.
Also, though, there=C2=A0is=C2=A0a backup mechanism, which is that if the c=
omputers fail, we can probably find someone to go walk across the streets o=
f Manhattan to deliver bonds and cash. Last week Industrial & Commercial Ba=
nk of China Ltd.=E2=80=99s US securities unit was hit by a ransomware attac=
k, =E2=80=9Crendering it unable to clear swathes of US Treasury trades afte=
r entities responsible for settling the transactions swiftly disconnected f=
rom the stricken system.=E2=80=9D And, so, down to the vaults. Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0Katherine Doherty, Liz Capo McCormick, and Alex Harris reporte=
d:

That forced ICBC to send the required settlement details to those parties b=
y a messenger carrying a thumb drive as the state-owned lender raced to lim=
it the damage.
The workaround =E2=80=94 described by market participants =E2=80=94 followe=
d the attack by suspected perpetrator Lockbit, a prolific criminal gang wit=
h ties to Russia that has also been linked to hits on Boeing Co., ION Tradi=
ng UK and the UK=E2=80=99s Royal Mail. The strike caused immediate disrupti=
on as market-makers, brokerages and banks were forced to reroute trades, wi=
th many uncertain when access would resume.

Fine, it=E2=80=99s thumb drives, not paper bond certificates, but still. In=
 some ways it is nice that the electronic global financial markets have clu=
msily evolved from older and more manual processes; there is still some anc=
ient memory of how to do stuff manually.

 =20
   =20
      Robot body language
   =20
 =20

You could have a model of investment analysis that is like:
=09Part of the job is about looking at financial statements, calculating ra=
tios, and figuring out which companies make a lot of money, which are cheap=
, etc.=09The other part of the job is meeting with corporate executives, sh=
aking their hands, getting a sense of their body language and their charact=
er, and deciding if they are good people who run a good company or bad peop=
le who don=E2=80=99t.

There is a quantitative analytical part, and a part about personality. Intu=
itively a computer should help with the first part. You can use a calculato=
r to compute the ratios. You can use Excel. You can use some more sophistic=
ated software system to get investment signals from millions of financial d=
ata points.
And then you can say =E2=80=9Cstill, I have to meet with management and sha=
ke their hands, because this is not a business of pure quantitative data; t=
here is a human component, and no computer can judge the firmness of a CEO=
=E2=80=99s handshake.=E2=80=9D Or can it? The Financial Times reports:

The idea that audio recordings could provide tips on executives=E2=80=99 tr=
ue emotions has caught the attention of some of the world=E2=80=99s largest=
 investors.
Many funds already use algorithms to trawl through transcripts of earnings =
calls and company presentations to glean signals from executives=E2=80=99 c=
hoice of words =E2=80=94 a field known as =E2=80=9CNatural Language Process=
ing=E2=80=9D or NLP. Now they are trying to find further messages in the wa=
y those words are spoken.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe idea is that audio captures more than just what is in text,=E2=
=80=9D said Mike Chen, head of alternative alpha research at Robeco, the as=
set manager. =E2=80=9CEven if you have a sophisticated semantic machine, it=
 only captures semantics.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Hesitation and filler words tend to be left out of transcripts, and AI can =
also pick up some=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmicrotremors=E2=80=9D that are imperceptibl=
e to the human ear.
Robeco, which manages over $80bn in algorithmically driven funds, making it=
 one of the largest quants, began adding audio signals picked up through AI=
 into its strategies earlier this year.

Three points here. The first is that if you are an algorithmic fund, you wi=
ll just on principle resist having a workflow that is like =E2=80=9Chave an=
 analyst listen to the conference call and write up her impressions of the =
executive=E2=80=99s confidence,=E2=80=9D because that sounds dumb and fuzzy=
 and subjective and labor-intensive and just not how one runs a quant fund.=
 But if you can have a=C2=A0computer=C2=A0listen to the conference call and=
 write up its impressions of the executive=E2=80=99s confidence, fine, good=
, that=E2=80=99s alpha.
The second is that=C2=A0mmmaybe=C2=A0the computer is better at it? =E2=80=
=9CMicrotremors=E2=80=9D? Like maybe humans are good at fooling humans with=
 confident misdirection, but the computers can=E2=80=99t be fooled so easil=
y?
The third is that this is sort of modeled=C2=A0as an iterated game in which=
:
=09Executives try to trick investors.
  [3]

=09Investors acquire computers that can spot the tricks.=09Executies adapt =
to be able to trick those computers.=09Investors get new computers.=09Etc.

Natural language processing of earnings calls is old hat now, which means n=
ot only that it=E2=80=99s not a competitive advantage (because every fund d=
oes it) but also that it doesn=E2=80=99t work as well (because executives a=
re now scripting themselves=C2=A0for the robots):

=E2=80=9CWe found tremendous value from transcripts,=E2=80=9D said Yin Luo,=
 head of quantitative research at Wolfe Research. =E2=80=9CThe problem that=
 has created for us and many others is that overall sentiment is becoming m=
ore and more positive=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89[because] compa=
ny management knows their messages are being analysed.=E2=80=9D
Multiple research papers have found that presentations have become increasi=
ngly positive since the emergence of NLP, as companies adjust their languag=
e to game the algorithms.=C2=A0

But now the robots=C2=A0listen to the calls, instead of just reading them, =
so they are not fooled by language choice; they can hear those microtremors=
. Now the executives have to refine their=C2=A0voices=C2=A0to fool the robo=
ts:
Just as companies have tried to adapt to text analysis, Pope predicted inve=
stor relations teams would start coaching executives to monitor voice tone =
and other behaviour that transcripts miss. Voice analysis struggles with tr=
ained actors who can convincingly stay in character, but replicating that m=
ay be easier said than done for executives.
One move is to get acting training. But clearly the better move, for execut=
ives, is:
=09Get a chatbot to write your earnings presentation, and responses to anal=
yst questions.=09Get a robot to read it for you in a soothing and convincin=
g way.=09Then the investors=E2=80=99 robots will listen to it and be like =
=E2=80=9Coh yes this CEO is very good, very confident, I like the cut of th=
is CEO=E2=80=99s jib.=E2=80=9D

Just cut out the human element everywhere.

 =20
   =20
      FTX 2.1
   =20
 =20

Some part of the promise of crypto is, or was, that it allows you to do thi=
ngs without=C2=A0trust. Instead of trusting a bank to keep track of your mo=
ney, you can rely on a distributed blockchain to do it. You don=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0have to trust anyone to maintain the blockchain, either: You can read=
 the open-source code underlying the blockchain, ponder its incentive mecha=
nisms and conclude =E2=80=9Cyes this blockchain will keep my money safe.=E2=
=80=9D A great deal of crypto is built on these sorts of ideas: =E2=80=9CCo=
de is law,=E2=80=9D and you can read the code rather than trusting the peop=
le involved or the system in which they operate.
Of course in actual practice a great deal of crypto consists of blindly tru=
sting your money to people,=C2=A0not=C2=A0on the blockchain,=C2=A0not=C2=A0=
in any sort of auditable way, and generally=C2=A0not=C2=A0people whom you o=
ught to trust. So many of them steal it! A quite typical form of interactio=
n with crypto is buying some crypto on a centralized exchange, keeping the =
crypto on that exchange rather than in your own wallet on the blockchain, a=
nd then having it stolen. And the people who steal it! Good lord.=C2=A0A wh=
ole lot of people in crypto might as well walk around with signs saying =E2=
=80=9CI will steal your money,=E2=80=9D and then people trust them with the=
ir money anyway, and then they steal it.
My view is that these are deep problems, and:
=09A trustless system relying only on code that everyone audits themselves =
is not actually workable: Humans are fallible, most of them have better thi=
ngs to do than audit smart-contract code, and a system that you can trust i=
s going to be more user friendly.=09No pitch works better for con men than =
saying =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t trust the system, the system is rigged ag=
ainst you, be an independent thinker, trust=C2=A0me=C2=A0instead.=E2=80=9D

But you could have a different view? I guess? For instance, you=C2=A0could =
have a view like:
=09It is very good and important to build a trustless system where people c=
an and do rely on auditable code rather than interpersonal trust.=09The bes=
t way to do that is to have the people promoting the system have =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0absolutely horrible credentials? Like ideally they would promote the =
trustless auditable system 15 minutes after stealing billions of dollars in=
 some previous trusted system? Then they could be like =E2=80=9Csee, use ou=
r system, it is auditable, and you know it is good because no one would=C2=
=A0trust us=C2=A0with their money, just look at us.=E2=80=9D

Is that incoherent? Probably. Anyway  the Wall Street Journal reports:

A group of former FTX executives, including one who served as a key witness=
 against Sam Bankman-Fried, are teaming up to build a new cryptocurrency ex=
change that aims to solve the problems that doomed their previous employer.
Trek Labs, a Dubai-based startup led by the former FTX general counsel Can =
Sun, received a license from the emirate=E2=80=99s crypto regulator last mo=
nth.=C2=A0
Another ex-FTX employee, Armani Ferrante, is chief executive of Trek=E2=80=
=99s holding company in the British Virgin Islands and also runs a partner =
firm, called Backpack, that designs and operates digital currency wallets. =
Sun=E2=80=99s former legal deputy, who is also Ferrante=E2=80=99s wife, sit=
s on Trek=E2=80=99s executive team, too. The venture is looking to sell a 1=
0% stake to investors at a valuation of over $100 million.
Sun and Ferrante said they wanted to use the lessons they learned from FTX=
=E2=80=99s failure to protect user funds. Backpack Exchange, the name under=
 which Trek Labs will do business, will use Backpack=E2=80=99s technology t=
o allow users to hold funds in their own =E2=80=9Cself-custody=E2=80=9D cry=
pto wallets that the exchange itself wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to unilateral=
ly access, they said.
Such wallets were designed using so-called multiparty computation technique=
s that require several parties to approve any transaction. Customers on Bac=
kpack Exchange, which plans to launch in beta later this month, would be ab=
le to verify their holdings at any time, they said.
It=E2=80=99s unclear what sort of reception they will face from investors a=
nd users given their background working at FTX. Ferrante=E2=80=99s name, no=
t Sun=E2=80=99s, appeared in a press release last month announcing the laun=
ch of Backpack Exchange.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIn a post-FTX world, you need trust and transparency to create a t=
rue alternative to the other players,=E2=80=9D Sun said.

Arguably you needed that in a pre-FTX world too! Arguably the best thing th=
at the=C2=A0general counsel of FTX=C2=A0could have done to solve the proble=
ms that doomed FTX was to=C2=A0solve them at FTX?=C2=A0Like, if you are the=
 top lawyer at a company, maybe don=E2=80=99t let the company steal billion=
s of dollars of customer money? Arguably that would have been better? But o=
f course once FTX=C2=A0did=C2=A0steal billions of dollars of customer money=
 that creates a business opportunity for its alumni to be like =E2=80=9Cnob=
ody has learned more from FTX than we have.=E2=80=9D Certainly not the cust=
omers! What on earth.

