<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33352147.257416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDkvYWRhbS1uZXVtYW5uLWlzLXNvLWdvb2QtYXQtdGhpc=
z9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTEzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB983e7f9e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote about</a>=C2=A0what I called =
a =E2=80=9Cprobabilistic billionaire.=E2=80=9D You create a company with so=
me long-shot idea that will be worth $1 trillion if it succeeds, you convin=
ce investors that you have a 1% chance of success, and you raise money at a=
 $10 billion valuation:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course eventually you will eith=
er succeed (with 1% probability) or fail (99%) at creating a trillion-dolla=
r company. If time goes by and you do not discover teleportation and you ge=
t bored and go back to your day job, then (let us assume) your probability =
of making $1 trillion goes to zero, and you are no longer a billionaire.</p=
></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was, of course, too simple. My toy exampl=
e of a company that was unlikely to succeed, but hugely valuable if it did,=
 was one trying to invent teleportation. But the=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>=
company that inspired the column was WeWork Inc. WeWork never achieved a $1=
 trillion valuation, and it seems unlikely that it ever will, and its found=
er long ago moved on to other endeavors. But WeWork still exists. It is=C2=
=A0<em>bankrupt</em>, sure, but it went bankrupt with=C2=A0a plan to restru=
cture its debts and get rid of its worst leases and try, once again, to mak=
e a go of it as an office-space sublessor. That is the sort of modest reaso=
nable business that:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Seems unlikely, stripped of the rheto=
ric of its charismatic founder, to be worth $1 trillion, but</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Is probably=C2=A0<em>viable</em>? Like, some peo=
ple in human history have figured out how to rent out office space, subdivi=
de it, and sublease it profitably? Why not WeWork?</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A teleportation company might have a 1% chance=
 of achieving a $1 trillion valuation and a 99% chance of achieving a $0 va=
luation, but very few companies are like that. Most companies are more like=
 WeWork, with a lot of potential outcomes in between $0 and $1 trillion. Ev=
en most ambitious risky startups might have a 1% chance of changing the wor=
ld and, you know, a 30% chance of making enough money to pay their bills wi=
th a bit left over for their investors. WeWork hasn=E2=80=99t quite gotten =
there yet, but maybe it will.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, WeWork at its peak raised m=
oney at a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33352147=
.257416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDc=
vd2V3b3JrLXMtYmFua3J1cHRjeS1jYXBzLXN3aWZ0LWRvd25mYWxsLWZvci00Ny1iaWxsaW9uLX=
N0YW5kb3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMTMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTExMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5814b0be" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  $47 billion valuation</a>, =
and=C2=A0before its first failed initial public offering in 2019 bankers we=
re throwing around <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/33352147.257416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjAtMDEtMjIvd2V3b3JrLXMtdmFsdWF0aW9uLXdhcy1mb3Itd2V3b3JrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExM=
TMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0=
bV90ZXJtPTIzMTExMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B0954196a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  valuations like $96 billion</a>, and it was absolutely=
 not making enough money to pay its bills at that point.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> (It was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33352=
147.257416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE1MzM1MjMv=
MDAwMTE5MzEyNTE5MjIwNDk5L2Q3ODE5ODJkczEuaHRtI3RvYzc4MTk4Ml8xMA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB9cad4bc2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> losing hundreds of millions of dollars</a> =
a year.) When WeWork was a darling of venture capital and SoftBank Group Co=
rp., it was because it was a potentially transformative company, the world=
=E2=80=99s first physical social network, blah blah blah, a 5% chance at a =
trillion dollars,=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>because it was a viable business. =
And then it went to the public markets and was like =E2=80=9C5% chance at a=
 trillion dollars??=E2=80=9D and the public markets were like =E2=80=9Clol =
absolutely not=E2=80=9D and there was an=C2=A0<em>extremely painful </em>tr=
ansition, which is now four years old and still ongoing, between the WeWork=
 of the past,=C2=A0a fast-growing speculative venture darling, and the stil=
l-possible WeWork of the future, a business that rents out office space and=
 subleases it, one day, one hopes, at a profit. And absolutely gajillions o=
f dollars of valuation have disappeared in that transition, because the amb=
itions of future WeWork=C2=A0are just much lower than the ambitions of past=
 WeWork.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">WeWork is probably=C2=A0the funniest, but ther=
e are lots of companies like this, companies that were funded by venture ca=
pital firms in the boom based on ambitious growth targets and plans to chan=
ge the world, and that failed to achieve those ambitions, but that are, you=
 know, fine, viable, possibly even profitable one day.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some ways that is the worst way to fail?=C2=
=A0For a startup founded by a visionary entrepreneur and funded by venture =
capitalists? Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The good outcome is you change the wo=
rld, your company is worth $1 trillion, and the founders and VCs are all ri=
ch and geniuses.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The disappointing=
 but acceptable outcome is you don=E2=80=99t, you shut down, the VCs write =
off their investment and the founder goes back to Big Tech or starts anothe=
r company, possibly with the same VCs. Everyone plans for a high likelihood=
 of this happening, and no one is shocked if it does.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">The awkward, what-do-we-do-now outcome is that you don=
=E2=80=99t change the world, the company chugs along, it makes enough money=
 to pay salaries and maybe open an office in Dallas and perhaps write a qua=
rterly dividend check to its VCs. But the VCs are like =E2=80=9CI do not wa=
nt a quarterly dividend check, a quarterly dividend check isn=E2=80=99t coo=
l, you know what is cool, a trillion dollars.=E2=80=9D And the founder is l=
ike =E2=80=9Cman I am paying myself $400,000 a year and working on the prob=
lem that excited me five years ago but I am not a billionaire and why am I =
in Dallas.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brilliant success is great, brilliant failure =
is fine, but ending up running a regular company seems like a letdown. =E2=
=80=9CWell I=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t invent teleportation, but I=E2=80=99ve got=
 a van and can move your furniture across town for $50 an hour.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33352147.257416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2=
NvbnRlbnQvN2VhYTQyZjEtNjMwMS00NWUzLTg0NjgtMmUyMmU2NjZjZjEx/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBba39afad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> a fun Financial Times story</a> about the scrap=
 dealers of the startup world:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors are shaking up the venture capital m=
arket by raising money to buy out start-ups that have been shunned by ventu=
re capitalists, taking advantage of economic headwinds to acquire promising=
 companies at a discount.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the years running up to 2022, VCs took mino=
rity stakes in new businesses with growth potential even if they lacked a q=
uick path to profitability. Steep rises in interest rates over the past yea=
r have changed that, hammering private valuations, forcing VCs to pull back=
 and leaving a swath of start-ups at risk of collapse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">New investment groups are raising tens of mill=
ions of dollars in funding with the intention of acquiring majority ownersh=
ip and operational control of start-ups in order to turn the businesses aro=
und.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It quotes Kjerstin Erickson of Arising Venture=
s:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Opportunities came up when =E2=80=9Cthe compan=
y has raised more money than they are worth in the market=E2=80=9D, she sai=
d. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll do the deal if we think there=E2=80=99s a real bu=
siness underneath.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This year the group =E2=80=94 which is structu=
red as a holding company rather than fund =E2=80=94 took out a billboard in=
 the heart of San Francisco with the slogan: =E2=80=9CWe invest in second c=
hances.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I love how shameful it is. =E2=80=9CDid you ac=
cidentally build a real business? Call us, we can help.=E2=80=9D Some inves=
tors like real businesses! Just, not VCs.=C2=A0There is an arbitrage. Here=
=E2=80=99s Oren Peleg of Resurge Growth Partners:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a real op=
portunity here to play a very important role, which is to help companies tr=
ansition from venture ownership to private equity ownership,=E2=80=9D Peleg=
 said. =E2=80=9CNo one is willing to send the hard message of saying this n=
eeds a reset, and that will be the role that we play.=E2=80=9D</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, venture ownership is for companies with f=
ast growth and no cash flows, and private equity ownership is for companies=
 with steady or declining cash flows. The transition is painful =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0ask WeWork =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, sometimes, necessary.=C2=A0</p>
