<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have a model of investment analysis =
that is like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Part of the job is about looking at f=
inancial statements, calculating ratios, and figuring out which companies m=
ake a lot of money, which are cheap, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">The other part of the job is meeting with corporate executives, sha=
king their hands, getting a sense of their body language and their characte=
r, and deciding if they are good people who run a good company or bad peopl=
e who don=E2=80=99t.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a quantitative analytical part, and a=
 part about personality. Intuitively a computer should help with the first =
part. You can use a calculator to compute the ratios. You can use Excel. Yo=
u can use some more sophisticated software system to get investment signals=
 from millions of financial data points.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then you can say =E2=80=9Cstill, I have to=
 meet with management and shake their hands, because this is not a business=
 of pure quantitative data; there is a human component, and no computer can=
 judge the firmness of a CEO=E2=80=99s handshake.=E2=80=9D Or can it? <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33352147.257416/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZWUyNzg4ZGQtYWNhNS00MjE0LThhMDgtZDg4MDgxZWFjMW=
I5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd269bdc1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">The Financial Times reports</=
a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea that audio recordings could provide t=
ips on executives=E2=80=99 true emotions has caught the attention of some o=
f the world=E2=80=99s largest investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many funds already use algorithms to trawl thr=
ough transcripts of earnings calls and company presentations to glean signa=
ls from executives=E2=80=99 choice of words =E2=80=94 a field known as =E2=
=80=9CNatural Language Processing=E2=80=9D or NLP. Now they are trying to f=
ind further messages in the way those words are spoken.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe idea is that audio captures more =
than just what is in text,=E2=80=9D said Mike Chen, head of alternative alp=
ha research at Robeco, the asset manager. =E2=80=9CEven if you have a sophi=
sticated semantic machine, it only captures semantics.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hesitation and filler words tend to be left ou=
t of transcripts, and AI can also pick up some=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmicrotremors=
=E2=80=9D that are imperceptible to the human ear.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robeco, which manages over $80bn in algorithmi=
cally driven funds, making it one of the largest quants, began adding audio=
 signals picked up through AI into its strategies earlier this year.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three points here. The first is that if you ar=
e an algorithmic fund, you will just on principle resist having a workflow =
that is like =E2=80=9Chave an analyst listen to the conference call and wri=
te up her impressions of the executive=E2=80=99s confidence,=E2=80=9D becau=
se that sounds dumb and fuzzy and subjective and labor-intensive and just n=
ot how one runs a quant fund. But if you can have a=C2=A0<em>computer=C2=A0=
</em>listen to the conference call and write up its impressions of the exec=
utive=E2=80=99s confidence, fine, good, that=E2=80=99s alpha.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second is that=C2=A0<em>mmmaybe=C2=A0</em>=
the computer is better at it? =E2=80=9CMicrotremors=E2=80=9D? Like maybe hu=
mans are good at fooling humans with confident misdirection, but the comput=
ers can=E2=80=99t be fooled so easily?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The third is that this is sort of modeled=C2=
=A0as an iterated game in which:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Executives try to trick investors.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investors acquire computers that =
can spot the tricks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Executies ada=
pt to be able to trick those computers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Investors get new computers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Etc.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Natural language processing of earnings calls =
is old hat now, which means not only that it=E2=80=99s not a competitive ad=
vantage (because every fund does it) but also that it doesn=E2=80=99t work =
as well (because executives are now scripting themselves=C2=A0for the robot=
s):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe found tremendous value from transc=
ripts,=E2=80=9D said Yin Luo, head of quantitative research at Wolfe Resear=
ch. =E2=80=9CThe problem that has created for us and many others is that ov=
erall sentiment is becoming more and more positive=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=
=80=89.=E2=80=89[because] company management knows their messages are being=
 analysed.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Multiple research papers have found that prese=
ntations have become increasingly positive since the emergence of NLP, as c=
ompanies adjust their language to game the algorithms.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now the robots=C2=A0<em>listen </em>to the=
 calls, instead of just reading them, so they are not fooled by language ch=
oice; they can hear those microtremors. Now the executives have to refine t=
heir=C2=A0<em>voices=C2=A0</em>to fool the robots:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just as companies have tried to ad=
apt to text analysis, Pope predicted investor relations teams would start c=
oaching executives to monitor voice tone and other behaviour that transcrip=
ts miss. Voice analysis struggles with trained actors who can convincingly =
stay in character, but replicating that may be easier said than done for ex=
ecutives.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One move is to get acting training. But clearl=
y the better move, for executives, is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Get a chatbot to write your earnings =
presentation, and responses to analyst questions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Get a robot to read it for you in a soothing and convincing=
 way.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then the investors=E2=80=99 =
robots will listen to it and be like =E2=80=9Coh yes this CEO is very good,=
 very confident, I like the cut of this CEO=E2=80=99s jib.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just cut out the human element everywhere.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX 2.1</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some part of the promise of crypto is, or was,=
 that it allows you to do things without=C2=A0<em>trust</em>. Instead of tr=
usting a bank to keep track of your money, you can rely on a distributed bl=
ockchain to do it. You don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have to trust anyone to maintain =
the blockchain, either: You can read the open-source code underlying the bl=
ockchain, ponder its incentive mechanisms and conclude =E2=80=9Cyes this bl=
ockchain will keep my money safe.=E2=80=9D A great deal of crypto is built =
on these sorts of ideas: =E2=80=9CCode is law,=E2=80=9D and you can read th=
e code rather than trusting the people involved or the system in which they=
 operate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course in actual practice a great deal of c=
rypto consists of blindly trusting your money to people,=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0=
</em>on the blockchain,=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>in any sort of auditable way=
, and generally=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>people whom you ought to trust. So m=
any of them steal it! A quite typical form of interaction with crypto is bu=
ying some crypto on a centralized exchange, keeping the crypto on that exch=
ange rather than in your own wallet on the blockchain, and then having it s=
tolen. And the people who steal it! Good lord.=C2=A0A whole lot of people i=
n crypto might as well walk around with signs saying =E2=80=9CI will steal =
your money,=E2=80=9D and then people trust them with their money anyway, an=
d then they steal it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My view is that these are deep problems, and:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A trustless system relying only on co=
de that everyone audits themselves is not actually workable: Humans are fal=
lible, most of them have better things to do than audit smart-contract code=
, and a system that you can trust is going to be more user friendly.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">No pitch works better for con men than=
 saying =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t trust the system, the system is rigged a=
gainst you, be an independent thinker, trust=C2=A0<em>me=C2=A0</em>instead.=
=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you could have a different view? I guess? =
For instance, you=C2=A0could have a view like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is very good and important to buil=
d a trustless system where people can and do rely on auditable code rather =
than interpersonal trust.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The best=
 way to do that is to have the people promoting the system have =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0absolutely horrible credentials? Like ideally they would promote the =
trustless auditable system 15 minutes after stealing billions of dollars in=
 some previous trusted system? Then they could be like =E2=80=9Csee, use ou=
r system, it is auditable, and you know it is good because no one would=C2=
=A0<em>trust us=C2=A0</em>with their money, just look at us.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that incoherent? Probably. Anyway <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33352147.257416/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2N1cnJlbmNpZXMva2V5LXdpdG5lc3MtYXQtc2FtLWJhbmtt=
YW4tZnJpZWQtdHJpYWwtdG8tbGF1bmNoLW5ldy1jcnlwdG8tZXhjaGFuZ2UtODBkMWVkY2U/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2e4c5512" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Wall Street Journal reports</a=
>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A group of former FTX executives, including on=
e who served as a key witness against Sam Bankman-Fried, are teaming up to =
build a new cryptocurrency exchange that aims to solve the problems that do=
omed their previous employer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trek Labs, a Dubai-based startup led by the fo=
rmer FTX general counsel Can Sun, received a license from the emirate=E2=80=
=99s crypto regulator last month.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another ex-FTX employee, Armani Ferrante, is c=
hief executive of Trek=E2=80=99s holding company in the British Virgin Isla=
nds and also runs a partner firm, called Backpack, that designs and operate=
s digital currency wallets. Sun=E2=80=99s former legal deputy, who is also =
Ferrante=E2=80=99s wife, sits on Trek=E2=80=99s executive team, too. The ve=
nture is looking to sell a 10% stake to investors at a valuation of over $1=
00 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sun and Ferrante said they wanted to use the l=
essons they learned from FTX=E2=80=99s failure to protect user funds. Backp=
ack Exchange, the name under which Trek Labs will do business, will use Bac=
kpack=E2=80=99s technology to allow users to hold funds in their own =E2=80=
=9Cself-custody=E2=80=9D crypto wallets that the exchange itself wouldn=E2=
=80=99t be able to unilaterally access, they said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Such wallets were designed using so-called mul=
tiparty computation techniques that require several parties to approve any =
transaction. Customers on Backpack Exchange, which plans to launch in beta =
later this month, would be able to verify their holdings at any time, they =
said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s unclear what sort of reception th=
ey will face from investors and users given their background working at FTX=
. Ferrante=E2=80=99s name, not Sun=E2=80=99s, appeared in a press release l=
ast month announcing the launch of Backpack Exchange.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn a post-FTX world, you need trust a=
nd transparency to create a true alternative to the other players,=E2=80=9D=
 Sun said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguably you needed that in a pre-FTX world to=
o! Arguably the best thing that the=C2=A0<em>general counsel of FTX=C2=A0</=
em>could have done to solve the problems that doomed FTX was to=C2=A0<em>so=
lve them at FTX?=C2=A0</em>Like, if you are the top lawyer at a company, ma=
ybe don=E2=80=99t let the company steal billions of dollars of customer mon=
ey? Arguably that would have been better? But of course once FTX=C2=A0<em>d=
id=C2=A0</em>steal billions of dollars of customer money that creates a bus=
iness opportunity for its alumni to be like =E2=80=9Cnobody has learned mor=
e from FTX than we have.=E2=80=9D Certainly not the customers! What on eart=
h.</p>
